159–1223":"1159–1223","1111–1176":"1111–1176","1110–1141":"1110–1141","before 1203":"before 1203","1176":"1176","1110":"1110","1141":"1141","1163":"1163","1238":"1238","1159":"1159","1203":"1203","1137":"1137","1147":"1147","1223":"1223","1111":"1111","1221":"1221","about 1137":"about 1137","about 1163":"about 1163","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Torquay, Devon, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braci","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Cheskel, Moshe, Chaim, Mendel, Pinchas, Bernat, Hershel, Meyer, Moche, Mort, Rivka, Rivky.","German: topographic name from Middle High German <i>brache</i> ‘fallow land, pastureland’, originally ‘newly plowed land’. Alternatively, a habitational name from any of the places called Braach (Hesse) or Brach (Baden-Württemberg, Franconia).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Barach  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Breach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donal.","English (Sussex): variant of   Brach  ."]},{"name":"Brecher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Chaim, Yosef, Baila, Chana, Ephraim, Herschel, Hershel, Meir, Meyer, Pnina, Shimon.  German Armin, Oskar, Bernd, Erwin, Gerhard.","English: variant of   Brach   2, from Middle English <i>breche</i>, Old English <i>brǣc</i>, <i>brēc</i> ‘newly cultivated land’, the <i>-er</i> suffix denoting an inhabitant.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from an agent derivative of German <i>brechen</i> ‘to break’, an occupational name for someone who crushed hemp or flax, or a nickname for a law breaker or evildoer."]},{"name":"Bracher","meanings":["English: from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>brech</i> ‘land broken up for cultivation’ (Old English <i>brǣc</i>, <i>brēc</i>), denoting a dweller by newly cultivated land. Compare   Brach   2 and   Breach  .","Swiss German: variant of German <b>Brachmann</b> (see   Brachman  ).","German: variant of   Brach   1."]},{"name":"Brachman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Brachmann</b>: variant of   Brach  , with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Brech","meanings":["German: variant of   Brach   1 or   Brecht  .","English: variant of   Breach   (see   Brach   2)."]},{"name":"Barach","meanings":["Americanized form of Croatian and Serbian <b>Barać</b> and <b>Barač</b> (see   Barac  ).","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): acronymic surname from the first letters of the Hebrew patronymic phrase <i>Ben Rabi Hayyim</i> ‘son of rabbi Hayyim’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aldulfus de Braci was born about 1137, in Shropshire, England, his father, Aldulf de Braci II, was 27 and his mother, Alice Briwere, was 29. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Agnes de Brus. He died before 1203, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"about 1137–before 1203":"umbes 1137–enne 1203","1137–1203":"1137–1203","1147–1203":"1147–1203","1163–1238":"1163–1238","–1221":"–1221","115